============================================================
DATASET DESCRIPTION
============================================================

The data used in this project were obtained from the Human Activity
Recognition Using Smartphones Dataset.

Data were collected from the accelerometer and gyroscope sensors
embedded in a Samsung Galaxy S smartphone.

Thirty volunteers performed six different activities while carrying
the smartphone. Sensor signals were measured and processed to produce
a set of variables describing motion and body activity.

============================================================
SOURCE DATA
============================================================

The following files from the original dataset were used:

features.txt
activity_labels.txt

train/X_train.txt
train/y_train.txt
train/subject_train.txt

test/X_test.txt
test/y_test.txt
test/subject_test.txt

The files contained in the Inertial Signals directories were not used.

============================================================
DATA CLEANING PROCESS
============================================================

The run_analysis.R script performs the following steps:

1. Reads the training and test datasets.

2. Merges the training and test datasets into one dataset.

3. Assigns descriptive variable names using features.txt.

4. Extracts only variables containing:

       mean()
       std()

5. Replaces activity identifiers with descriptive activity names
   using activity_labels.txt.

6. Cleans variable names to improve readability by removing
   special characters such as parentheses and dashes.

7. Creates a second tidy dataset containing the average of every
   measurement variable for each activity and subject.

8. Exports the resulting tidy dataset to:

       tidyData.txt

============================================================
TIDY DATASET STRUCTURE
============================================================

Observations: 180

Variables: 68

The dataset contains:

- 30 subjects
- 6 activities
- 66 averaged measurement variables

Each row represents a unique combination of:

       Subject + Activity

Each measurement variable contains the average value for that
subject/activity combination.

